				<td colspan="2"><span>I am not possitive they haven't rescinded the statement, but they had announced that eq2 wouldgo on the all-access pass.  That runs 21.95 a month, so if you happen to dabble in planet side oranything, its a great deal. And the game is expensive, i'll admit that.  However the graphics are great (the good city of Qeynos is beautiful, freeport is pretty ugly, as it issupposedto be) and thegameplay is refreshingly different while still being famliar.  For the people cncerned about thamajor changes being addedlate in the beta, don't be afraid.  They have  working on thecode for a while, and are reacting to problems very quickly.  They worked on game balance issueswith a limited set of spells/ablities to make the evaluation easier to understand.  Nowthey can swap in/out abilities that fit the molds they created very easily.  All they haveto do is iron out small specific bugs with each spell/ability, and react when playersfigure outnew ways to abuse the system (play creatively, play to the max, or what ever youwant to call it).
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, all I am saying is that the progress of thegame is advancing faster the closer they get to release, not slower.  I think it will be as ready or more so than most MMORPGs are at release.
<br />

<br />
And just to taunt you if you haven't already read about it, player housing has just gotten a great revamp.  Personal addresses, special housng areas for larger guild houses, new items, and more.  The character customization you get to do as you level is not massively drastic, it will not compensatefor crapy equipment for example, but is helpful.  There is stll work going into theablities, I know because 2 of my characters of the same type have different versions of thesame ability granted by the same quest.  But it is very promising.  Everyone will get ablities similar to how paladins get slay-undead in EQ1, but you get to pick the races you want to affect.  Now go read the forums on EQ2 for more details =)</span></td>
